[1] China (Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region), unidentified avians
Date: Sun, 2 Jul 2006
From: Mary Marshall
<tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Bloomberg.com, 1 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=adL6DwiIHAkE&refer=asia>

China's Agriculture Ministry confirms new outbreak of bird flu
--------------------------------------------------------------
China's agriculture ministry has confirmed a new outbreak of avian influenza
in the north western Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, according to a
government statement. The outbreak occurred in Zhongwei city in Ningxia, the
ministry stated on its website [on 1 Jul]. The national avian influenza
reference laboratory on 29 Jun 2006 confirmed the H5N1 strain of the virus
in dead birds, it said.
The statement did not say how many birds were involved or whether it was
among farm-raised poultry or wild birds. Ministry officials have been sent
to the region to begin quarantine and disinfection operations, it said.
China has recorded 36 outbreaks of avian flu among birds since last October,
according to Agence France-Presse. China has reported a total of 19 human
cases of H5N1, of which 12 were fatal, according to the World Health
Organization.
Since January, at least 54 people have died from the H5N1 avian influenza
strain in Azerbaijan, Cambodia, China, Djibouti, Egypt, Indonesia, Iraq and
Turkey, according to WHO.
[byline: Xiao Yu]
